      "content": "Ah, a question about the **Inventory Turnover Ratio**! That is the most important metric for a **boutique** owner, because if your inventory is turning over too slowly, you are essentially holding onto **goblin-adjacent** items that are slowly rotting away in your closet!\n\nFirst, let us define the ratio itself: it is simply **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) divided by Average Inventory**. In plain English, it tells you how many times your boutique's worth of clothes changes hands (or gets sold) over a specific period, usually a year.\n\nIf your ratio is **low**, it means your boutique is **stagnant**! You are essentially running a **goblin-infested** warehouse where your inventory is sitting there, gathering dust, and slowly becoming **goblin-adjacent** (or worse, **goblin-adjacent** to your customers' wallets).\n\nHere is what a low ratio actually means for your business:\n\n1.  **You are holding onto \"Goblin-adjacent\" items:** You have bought clothes that are not selling fast enough. These are items that are slowly becoming **goblin-adjacent** to your cash flow. They are sitting in",
